🔧 EMG Instruments

Comprehensive guide to electrodiagnostic equipment including electrode types, amplifiers, filters, and stimulators. Learn technical specifications, setup procedures, and troubleshooting techniques.

Equipment guide Technical specs Setup procedures Troubleshooting

⚡ Electronic Circuitry (Ohm's Law)

Ohm's Law
I = V/R
Current (Amperes) = Voltage (Volts) / Resistance (Ohms)

Electric current intensity equals voltage from electromotor source divided by resistance.

📍 Electrodes

Purpose: Record or stimulate skin surface, muscle, or nerve

Key Requirement: Low impedance between electrode and skin (remove lotions, oils, gels)

🎯 Recording Electrodes

Active Electrode (G1)
  • SNAP: Placed directly over nerve
  • CMAP: Placed over motor endplate
  • Records electrical activity from nerve action potential
Reference Electrode (G2)
  • Placed over electrically neutral area
  • Usually tendon or bone
  • Used during sensory or motor nerve studies

🔍 Surface vs Needle Electrodes

Type Description Advantages Disadvantages
Surface Electrodes Metal or disposable stickers with conductive gel Non-invasive, easy to apply May have more interference
Monopolar Needle 22-30 gauge Teflon-coated, 0.15-0.2 mm² tip • Inexpensive
• Omni-directional
• Less painful
• Larger recording area		 • Requires separate reference
• Teflon fraying
• More interference
Concentric Needle 24-26 gauge with inner wire active electrode • Standardized area
• Less interference
• Used for quantitative EMG		 • Unidirectional
• Smaller recording area
• More painful
Bipolar Needle Active and reference wires within lumen • Best MUAP isolation
• Less artifact		 • Expensive
• More painful
Single-Fiber 25-μm diameter wire (active) • Individual fiber assessment
• Jitter analysis
• NMJ disorder evaluation		 • Not for traditional EMG
• Expensive

⚡ Nerve Stimulation

🎚️ Stimulation Intensity Levels

Threshold Stimulus

Minimum intensity to produce detectable evoked potential

Maximal Stimulus

No further increase in evoked potential with added intensity

Submaximal Stimulus

⚠️ Problem: Can cause falsely lower amplitude and prolonged latency

Supramaximal Stimulus

✅ Standard: 20% above maximal - typically used for NCS

🔌 Bipolar Stimulator

  • Cathode (-): Attracts positive charges from axon
  • Anode (+): Attracts negative charges from axon
  • Anodal Block: Hyperpolarization when poles reversed

⏱️ Stimulation Parameters

  • Duration: Usually 0.1 msec (0.5 msec for monopolar needle)
  • Averaging: Improves signal-to-noise ratio by √(number of averages)
  • Ground Electrode: Zero-voltage reference between recording and stimulating electrodes

🔧 Signal Processing Components

📡 Differential Amplifier

  • Responds to alternating currents
  • Cancels common waveforms, amplifies differences
  • CMRR: ≥90 dB (higher = more efficient)
  • High impedance, low internal noise

🔧 Filters

Standard Settings:
  • Sensory NCS: 20 Hz to 10 kHz
  • Motor NCS: 2 Hz to 10 kHz
  • EMG: 20 Hz to 10 kHz
Filter Effects on Waveforms:
Elevating Low-Frequency Filter:
  • ✓ Reduces peak latency
  • ✗ Reduces amplitude
  • Changes bi- to triphasic
  • Does not change onset latency
Reducing High-Frequency Filter:
  • ✗ Prolongs peak latency
  • ✗ Reduces amplitude
  • Creates longer negative spike
  • ✗ Prolongs onset latency

⚙️ Standard Technical Settings

Study Type Sweep Speed Sensitivity Notes
Sensory NCS 5 msec 10 µV Higher sensitivity for small potentials
Motor NCS 2 msec 5 mV Lower sensitivity for larger potentials
EMG - Insertional 10 msec 100 µV For insertional activity assessment
EMG - Recruitment 10 msec 1 mV For recruitment pattern analysis

🛠️ Artifact Minimization

Stimulus Artifact Reduction:

  • Place ground electrode between recording and stimulating electrodes
  • Appropriate anode and cathode placement
  • Clean skin from dirt, perspiration, and lotions
  • Proper electrode impedance matching

Common Interference Sources:

  • 60 Hz line interference
  • EMG audio feedback
  • Needle artifact
  • Fluorescent lights
  • Preamplifier proximity to machine

📥 AFFERENT
(Sensory Input) 		CN V

Response Latency Anatomical Course Distribution Clinical Significance

(Early Response) 		~10-13 ms Through the PONS

📋 Clinical Notes

🔍 Key Clinical Points
  • CN: Cranial Nerve
  • Electrically evoked corneal reflex analogue
  • Essential brainstem function test
⚡ Stimulation Options
  • Supraorbital nerve (most common)
  • Infraorbital nerve
  • Mental nerve

🔬 Blink Reflex Abnormality Patterns

Pattern Condition Stimulate Affected Side Stimulate Unaffected Side Key Features
A Normal Ipsilateral R1 + Bilateral R2 Ipsilateral R1 + Bilateral R2 All responses normal
B Incomplete Right Trigeminal Lesion Delayed R1 + R2 (both sides) Normal R1 + R2 (both sides) Unilateral sensory delay
C Complete Right Trigeminal Lesion Absent R1 + R2 (both sides) Normal R1 + R2 (both sides) Complete sensory loss
D Incomplete Right Facial Lesion Delayed ipsi R1+R2, normal contra R2 Normal ipsi R1+R2, delayed contra R2 Affected side abnormal regardless of stimulation
E Complete Right Facial Lesion Absent ipsi R1+R2, normal contra R2 Normal ipsi R1+R2, absent contra R2 Complete motor loss on affected side
F Coma/Medullary Interneurons Normal R1, abnormal R2 Normal R1, abnormal R2 R2 pathway disrupted bilaterally
G Right Medullary Lesion (CN V nucleus) Normal R1, abnormal ipsi R2 Normal R1, abnormal contra R2 Unilateral medullary involvement
H Demyelinating Peripheral Neuropathy Delayed/absent responses Delayed/absent responses Bilateral conduction slowing

🎯 R1 & R2 Clinical Significance

⚡ R1 Component

📊 Characteristics:
  • Latency: Early response (~10-13 ms)
  • Pathway: Oligosynaptic
  • Location: Ipsilateral only
  • Stability: Consistent and reliable
🎯 Affected by Lesions of:
🧠 Trigeminal Nerve Afferent pathway
🧠 Pons Central processing
😊 Facial Nerve Efferent pathway
🔍 Clinical Use:
Primary marker for brainstem integrity

⚡ R2 Component

📊 Characteristics:
  • Latency: Late response (~30-40 ms)
  • Pathway: Polysynaptic
  • Location: Bilateral
  • Stability: Variable, state-dependent
⚠️ Affected by:
🧠 Consciousness Level Drugs, Habituation
🤝 Parkinson's Disease Extrapyramidal system
🧠 Lateral Medullary Wallenberg syndrome
🔍 Clinical Use:
Sensitive to functional states

🚨 Essential Clinical Knowledge

🔬 Blink Reflex Fundamentals

The blink reflex is an electrically evoked analogue to the corneal reflex, utilizing the 3rd branch of the trigeminal nerve. The response propagates into the medulla and branches to innervate facial muscles.

⚡ Stimulation Sites:
  • Supraorbital nerve
  • Infraorbital nerve
  • Mental nerve
📍 Recording Approaches:
  • Subcostal (most common)
  • Lower lateral intercostals
  • Substernal
💡 Clinical Pearl: Subcostal approach preferred for safety and reliable needle positioning

📋 Quick Reference Guide

R1 Abnormal
→ Structural brainstem lesion
R2 Abnormal
→ Functional or metabolic issues

📊 Clinical EMG Patterns

Clinical EMG pattern recognition guide featuring motor unit action potential (MUAP) analysis, abnormal spontaneous activity, and interference patterns for different pathological conditions.

Pattern recognition MUAP analysis Clinical correlation Diagnostic guide

⚡ MUAP Parameters

Parameter Description Normal Value Clinical Significance
Amplitude Peak-to-peak measurement of muscle fibers near needle electrode ~1 mV ↑ Reinnervation; ↓ Fiber loss; Variable in NMJ disorders
Rise Time Time from baseline to negative peak <500 μsec Indicates needle proximity to motor unit
Duration Initial departure to final return to baseline 5-15 msec ↑ Collateral sprouting (>15); ↓ Fiber loss (<5)
Turns Direction changes not crossing baseline (serrations) Variable Increased in reinnervation/pathology
Phases Baseline crossings + 1 (synchronicity measure) 2-4 ≥5 = Polyphasic (fiber dropout, reinnervation)

🔍 MUAP Abnormalities

Abnormality Type Characteristics Primary Conditions Mechanism
LDLA Polyphasic Long-Duration, Large-Amplitude potentials Neuropathies, chronic myopathies Denervation → reinnervation → collateral sprouting
SDSA Polyphasic Short-Duration, Small-Amplitude potentials Myopathies, NMJ disorders, severe neuropathy Muscle fiber dropout
"Neuropathic" LDLA MUAPs (term discouraged) Traditional neuropathic pattern Reinnervation process
"Myopathic" SDSA MUAPs (term discouraged) Traditional myopathic pattern Muscle fiber loss
Unstable Potentials Variable amplitude, duration, slope NMJ disorders, motor neuron disease Irregular blocking, reinnervation
Satellite Potentials Small, time-locked trailing potentials Early reinnervation Newly formed, slowly conducting sprouts
Doublet/Multiple 2+ MUAPs firing together semirhythmically Ischemia, tetany, motor neuron disease Abnormal motor unit firing patterns
Giant Potentials Extremely large MUAPs (>5 mV) Poliomyelitis, chronic neuropathy Massive reinnervation

📈 Motor Unit Recruitment Patterns

✅ Normal MUAP Recruitment - "Rule of Fives"

📊 Sequential Recruitment Pattern:
Step 1st MUAP 2nd MUAP 3rd MUAP 4th MUAP
Initial 5 Hz — — —
Step 2 10 Hz 5 Hz — —
Step 3 15 Hz 10 Hz 5 Hz —
Step 4 20 Hz 15 Hz 10 Hz 5 Hz
🔑 Key Principle: Each new motor unit begins firing at ~5 Hz as existing units increase their firing rate

⚡ Early Recruitment (Myopathic)

📋 Characteristics:
  • Pattern: Many MUAPs fire early with mild contraction
  • Timing: Abnormally early activation
  • Force: Reduced force per motor unit
🎯 Mechanism:
Loss of muscle fibers → Reduced force generation → More motor units needed for same force
🏥 Common Conditions:
  • Myopathies
  • Muscle fiber loss
  • Some NMJ disorders

📉 Reduced Recruitment (Neuropathic)

📋 Characteristics:
  • Pattern: Fewer MUAPs than expected
  • Effort: Even with maximal contraction
  • Available Units: Reduced motor unit pool
🎯 Mechanism:
Loss of motor neurons → Fewer available motor units → Inadequate recruitment
🏥 Common Conditions:
  • Neuropathies
  • Motor neuron loss
  • Severe myopathies

🩺 Clinical Decision Making

Normal
5 Hz rule applies
Early Recruitment
Think Myopathy
Reduced Recruitment
Think Neuropathy

🌊 Spontaneous Activity

✅ Normal Spontaneous Activity

  • Endplate Noise: MEPP & EPP
  • Location: Only at endplate regions
  • Sound: Sea shell murmur / sputtering fat
  • Clinical: Normal finding

⚠️ Abnormal Spontaneous Activity

  • Fibrillations: Denervated muscle fibers
  • Positive Sharp Waves: Membrane instability
  • Complex Discharges: Various patterns
  • Clinical: Pathological finding

📊 Normal Endplate Activity Characteristics

Parameter MEPP
(Miniature Endplate Potential)		 EPP
(Endplate Potential)
Initial Deflection Negative
(monophasic)		 Negative
(biphasic)
Duration 0.5–1.0 msec 2.0–4.0 msec
Amplitude 10–50 μV <1,000 μV (1 mV)
Rate 150 Hz 50–100 Hz
Rhythm Irregular Irregular
Origin Endplate Endplate/provoked
Characteristic Sound 🐚 "Sea shell murmur" 🍳 "Sputtering fat in frying pan"

⚡ Fibrillation Potentials & Positive Sharp Waves Grading Scale

Grade Clinical Characteristics Severity
0 None detected Normal
1+ Persistent single runs >1 second in two areas Mild
2+ Moderate runs >1 second in three or more areas Moderate
3+ Many discharges in most muscle regions Severe
4+ Continuous discharges in all areas of the muscle Very Severe

🩺 Clinical Significance

✅ Grade 0-1+
Normal to minimal denervation
May be acceptable in some contexts
⚠️ Grade 2-4+
Significant denervation
Indicates active nerve/muscle pathology

📊 Electrodiagnostic Findings Timeline

TimeAbnormality
0• Decreased recruitment
• Decreased recruitment interval
• Prolonged F wave
• Abnormal H-reflex (S1 radiculopathy)
4 days• Decreased compound motor action potential amplitude (approximately 50% compared to opposite side) in severe cases
1 week• Abnormal spontaneous activity occurs first in the paraspinals
• They can be normal if: They become reinnervated, The posterior primary rami are spared
• They can be the only abnormal finding 10%-30% of the time
2 weeks• Abnormal spontaneous activity beginning in the limbs
3 weeks• Abnormal activity present in both the paraspinals and limbs
5-6 weeks• Reinnervation begins
6 months to 1 year• Increased amplitude from reinnervated motor unit. Reinnervation complete
Every 3-4 months• Serial EMG can be performed in intervals to monitor for reinnervation as clinically warranted

🔬 NCS vs EMG in Nerve Injuries

⚡ Nerve Conduction Studies (NCS)

📋 Primary Role: Evaluate superimposed neurologic pathologies in radiculopathies
Note: Rarely abnormal in pure radiculopathies
🔍 Key Findings:
SNAP ✅ Normal if lesion proximal to DRG
CMAP ⚠️ Normal or reduced
• Lesion distal to motor neuron
• May be normal in demyelination
🕐 Late Responses:
  • H-reflex: Possibly abnormal in S1 radiculopathy
    • Not pathognomonic
  • F-waves: Not sensitive or specific
    • Multiple root innervation → normal latency

🔬 Needle EMG

📋 Gold Standard: Most sensitive test for radiculopathy diagnosis
🎯 Diagnostic Criteria:
Required Findings:
  • Abnormalities in ≥2 muscles
  • Same spinal nerve root
  • Different peripheral nerves
🔢 Optimal Muscle Sampling:
Ideal 6 muscles total
5 peripheral + 1 paraspinal
Minimum 4 muscles
Prioritize weak muscles
⚡ Key Abnormalities:
  • Fibrillations (FIBs)
  • Positive Sharp Waves (PSWs)
  • Found in muscles from same root, different nerves

💡 Clinical Pearls

🔍 When NCS May Be Abnormal:
  • Superimposed peripheral neuropathy
  • Concomitant entrapment syndromes
  • Multiple level involvement
⚠️ EMG Limitations:
  • May miss pure sensory radiculopathies
  • Chronic injuries may show reinnervation
  • Random sampling may miss focal lesions

🔍 Radiculopathy Etiology

Common Causes

  • Herniated nucleus pulposus (HNP): Most common; typically seen in adults <50 years of age
  • Spinal stenosis: Typically seen in adults >50 years of age

Uncommon Causes - "HI MADAM" Mnemonic:

  • H - Herpes zoster
  • I - Inflammatory: Tuberculosis (TB), Lyme disease, HIV, syphilis, cryptococcus, and sarcoidosis
  • M - Metastasis
  • A - Arachnoiditis: Myelogram, surgery, steroids, and anesthesia
  • D - Diabetes mellitus
  • A - Abscess
  • M - Mass in the spine: Meningioma, neurofibroma, leukemia, lipoma, synovial cysts, and hematoma

📊 Key NCS Parameters

⏱️
Latency
Onset Latency

Time for stimulus to initiate evoked potential

Peak Latency

Measured at peak amplitude

🏃
Conduction Velocity

Definition: Speed of impulse travel

Primary Factor: Myelin integrity

Formula: Distance ÷ Time

📈
Amplitude
Motor (CMAP)

Reflects number of viable motor axons

Sensory (SNAP)

Reflects axonal integrity & fiber count

📋 Quick Reference Summary

👶 CV develops from 50% → 100% by age 3-5
🧓 CV decreases 1-2 m/s per decade after 50
🌡️ CV decreases 2.4 m/s per 1°C drop
📏 Standard temps: 32°C (UE), 30°C (LE)

🧪 Radiation vs Tumor Plexopathy

Critical distinction in plexopathy etiology with different clinical patterns and prognosis

☢️ Radiation Plexopathy

Post-treatment
📍 Site Upper trunk
⚡ EMG Finding Myokymia
🔄 Sensation Painless
⏰ Timing Months to years post-radiation
🔬 Mechanism:
Fibrosis Vascular damage
VS

🎯 Tumor Plexopathy

Malignant
📍 Site Lower trunk
👁️ Clinical Sign Horner's syndrome
😰 Sensation Painful
📈 Timing Variable, progressive
🔬 Mechanism:
Direct compression Invasion

🔑 Key Differentiating Points

⚡ Myokymia strongly suggests radiation etiology
😰 Pain more common in tumor plexopathy
📍 Location: Radiation (upper) vs Tumor (lower)
👁️ Horner's syndrome suggests lower trunk/tumor

🔄 Nerve Anastomoses

Anatomical nerve connections that can significantly impact electrodiagnostic findings and clinical interpretation.

📊 Anastomoses at a Glance

Anastomosis Location Frequency Key Clinical Impact
Martin Gruber Forearm 15-31% Masks median nerve severity
Riche-Cannieu Hand ~77% Preserves thenar in ulnar lesions
Berrettini Hand ~80% Alters 4th/5th digit sensation
Accessory Deep Peroneal Lower leg ~28% EDB preservation in foot drop

🤝 Martin Gruber Anastomosis

15-31% Population

🔗 Connection

Median Nerve (AIN) → Ulnar Nerve Forearm

⚡ EDX Findings

📈 Ulnar CMAP amplitude higher at elbow vs wrist
🎯 Collision technique confirms crossover
⚠️ May mask median nerve injury severity

🏥 Clinical Impact

✅ Preserves hand function in median injuries
⚠️ Can confuse carpal tunnel diagnosis
🔍 Critical for surgical planning

Riche-Cannieu

77%
Deep Ulnar ↔ Median (Thenar)
Key Point: Preserves thenar function in ulnar nerve lesions

Berrettini

80%
Superficial Ulnar ↔ Median Digital
Key Point: Alters sensory patterns in 4th & 5th digits

Accessory Deep Peroneal

28%
Superficial Peroneal → Deep Peroneal Territory
Key Point: May innervate EDB in foot drop cases

🔬 Clinical Testing Strategy

🚨 Red Flags (When to Suspect Variants)

🔍 Clinical findings don't match EDX results
💪 Unexpected muscle preservation in nerve injury
📊 Significant CMAP amplitude differences between sites
🗺️ Atypical sensory or motor distribution patterns

🔬 Specialized Testing Techniques

Collision Studies
Stimulate both nerves simultaneously to detect crossover
Incremental Stimulation
Gradually increase stimulus intensity to unmask connections
Inching Technique
Short segment stimulation to precisely localize anatomy
Volume Conduction Assessment
Multiple recording sites to differentiate true vs artifact
